		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Splash has become Wet indeed...<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.83)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13846'>Marcel "Gullecram" Matijssen</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=13846&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 29, 2005</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Due to the lack of articles on Decktech, I (bored as I am) have written one, just to keep you awake…<br />
<br />
Splashing a card in the LOTR ccg, was usually a Meta-call or necessity, like Enquea, sniper king and Greenleaf and Aragorn, ROTN. When Rotation kicked in, these three splash cards were rotated out, and I saw all around me, players searching for new spashable cards to battle the Meta.<br />
<br />
Rubber chicken (Zach Shephard) has written an excellent article on the splashable cards that are left after Rotation, check out the link here:<br />
<br />
http://lotronline.decipher.com/articles/MIMvol1Splash.shtml<br />
<br />
However, I am seeing more and more players change not to Splash cards, but Splash “Packages”, containing up to 5 or 10 cards of a certain culture that does not really help the fellowship or shadow´s theme. Why is that?, simple, because of the increasing threat of the shadow side of LOTR decks. Splashing a single card simply does not cut it anymore against most decks. Let me give you an example:<br />
<br />
Before rotation, splashing a single Sam, son of hamfast would keep most, if not all burden decks at bay. Even dropping sam at site 7 would be enough to win. If you could splash a single Sam now, you’ll be more likely to be corrupted before Sam even hits the table. One-Hit-Wonders are not good enough anymore in most cases. Don’t get me wrong, all the cards listed in Rubber chicken’s article are excellent cards for splashing, but to fight the greater force, you’ll need more cards.<br />
<br />
What is currently being used as a “splash-package” you ask?, here’s a top 3 list of the ones I have seen for fellowship sides, and I will also explain why it is that good.<br />
<br />
At the top of the list, at NR. 1 is the Smeagol package:<br />
<br />
More and more players are starting to see the greatness of this package, it contains mostly the following cards:<br />
<br />
1. Smeagol, Always helps, 1 copy, used in starting fellowship<br />
2. Follow smeagol, 1 or 2 copies<br />
3. Don’t look at them, 1 or 2 copies<br />
4. Not listening, 1 copy<br />
<br />
Why is it good? Lets look at it and see what it can do. <br />
For as low as 3 cards, you could have the following: A 1 burden speed bump when needed, controlling the sitepath in your favor, cycling unneeded cards like crazy, Kill almost all minions out there. Castamirs, Enduring enquea´s, Saurons, I have seen them all fall at the cost of 2 threats and 3 cards. What decks are using this package now? Dwarves mostly, for the awesome Sitepath controlling and Twilight choking. Second is the Hobbit deck, simply because it functions so well with Unheeded, and having a lot of Dwelling and forest sites laying ahead of those little buggers seems to do them well, so I heard.<br />
<br />
But I think this will not stop here, Knights, Rohan, Ents…..Holy Schnitsel, every deck could gain a lot with this package. I can see no reason for not including this little Smeagol Package if you have the space for it.<br />
<br />
At nr 2 in the list is the all known, Gandalf package:<br />
<br />
It started way back in Fellowship block with Gandalf, Friend of the shire folk or Grey Pelgrim, together with 2 Sleep caradras. Now, after Rotations, the package looks more or less like this:<br />
<br />
1. Gandalf, Leader of the company, 1 or 4 copies<br />
2. Glamdring, foe hammer, 1 or 2 copies<br />
3. Grown suddenly tall, 1 or 2 copies<br />
4. Roll of thunder, 1,2 or 3 copies<br />
5. Terrible and evil, 1 or 2 copies<br />
6. Well traveled, 1 or 2 copies<br />
7. Send back, 1 copy<br />
<br />
Why is it good? Lets look at it and see what it can do:<br />
<br />
For 6-10 cards, you could have the following: semi-permanent strength increase for ALL companions, Burden removal, condition removal, possession removal, direct wounding, site path control and when push comes to shove, it can get rid of ANY minion at the cost of gandalf (send back). Granted, this package needs a lot more cards than smeagol´s does, that is why you do not see it in many decks. Dwarves, Hobbit and Rohan decks use it for Strength increase and Condition & Burden removal. I have seen running Gondor (noble leaders) decks that uses him and Radagast, together with Send back and Out of the high airs, to double and triple their way into victory. Try it out if you have the space for it in your deck.<br />
<br />
At nr three is the Eowyn package.<br />
<br />
Lady of Rohan was used to “go over 5”, meaning that you could “safely” go over 5 companions, because she would keep Enquea at bay for at least 1 site. Sorry to say, that will not be enough anymore against the threats offered now by shadow cards, the new Cantea-black assassin does not care about dealing wounds.<br />
<br />
What does the package looks like?<br />
<br />
1. Eowyn, Lady of Ithilien 1,2 or 3 copies, usually starting<br />
2. Brego, 1 copy<br />
3. Leowyn, 1  or 2 copies<br />
4. Coif, 1 copy<br />
5. Eowyn´s sword, denhelms blade<br />
6. Arrowslits, 1 or 2 copies<br />
<br />
Why is it good, lets look and see what it can do:<br />
<br />
For 4-10 cards, you could have the following: Indirect wounding in multiples, possession removal, cycling & healing. She can deal more wounds than greenleaf ever could, and early in the game (site 2-6) can clean the board of minions for the double move (or just survive). It is deadly against minions who like to have a lot of vitality, like Nazguls and Enduring southrons. <br />
Elves use this package, because it functions nicely with their archery. The same goes for every fellowship that has any kind of direct wounding, or direct exerting ability.  New wounding/exerting decks are popping up everywhere with this package. IMO, It functions the best in a deck that chokes a little, so that few minions can make it into play. <br />
<br />
If you ever find yourself short of cards to play in your deck, try one of these packages, and see for yourself if it fits in your deck. I will bet that there will be more and more of these splash packages being invented over time, with cards like Heathen, Ghan bury Ghan, Faramirs sword etc…<br />
<br />
Try for yourself and see if you can find or make one yourself that fits nicely in that 3-7 card gap you always seem to have in your deck when building it.<br />
<br />
<br />
Stay tuned. I might write another article, god forbid…<br />
<br />
Gullecram.<br />
<br />
